<Base title="HUMANFILE — ostk governance" description="The operator identity document. Tells the OS who you are and how you work.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>HUMANFILE</h1>
    <p class="lead">Your compiled identity. The OS reads this at boot and calibrates to you.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      HUMANFILE is the document that tells the OS who you are, how you like to work,
      and what you authorize agents to do on your behalf. Not a config file — a governance document.
      You write it once. Every agent that runs under your OS reads it.
    </p>
    <p>Location: <code>.haystack/HUMANFILE</code> in your project root.</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code># HUMANFILE — your-name

## Identity
- Name: Your Name
- Handle: @you
- Timezone: US/Eastern

## Working style
- Compact output preferred
- Show work in files, not chat
- Status updates in tack format

## Autonomy grants
- File writes: approved without confirmation
- Test runs: approved without confirmation
- Git commits: ask first
- External API calls: ask first

## Tack preferences
typo_correction: suggest     # suggest | silent | off

## Vault
secrets:
  ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: authorized
  OPENROUTER_API_KEY: authorized</code></pre>

    <h2>Fields</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Section</th><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Identity</td><td>Name</td><td>string</td><td>Your name. Used in audit attribution.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Identity</td><td>Handle</td><td>@string</td><td>Your operator handle. Must be unique on this OS.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Identity</td><td>Timezone</td><td>TZ string</td><td>Used for log timestamps in your local time.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Working style</td><td>(free text)</td><td>lines</td><td>Prose preferences. Agents read and adapt.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Autonomy grants</td><td>action: approved/ask first</td><td>map</td><td>What agents can do without asking. See below.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tack preferences</td><td>typo_correction</td><td>suggest/silent/off</td><td>How the OS handles typos in tack input.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Vault</td><td>KEY: authorized/denied</td><td>map</td><td>Which API keys agents are allowed to use.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Autonomy grants</h2>
    <p>
      Autonomy grants are the trust boundary. They define what agents can do without
      interrupting you for confirmation. Start conservative and loosen as you observe behavior.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Action</th><th>Approved</th><th>Ask first</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>File writes</td><td>Agent edits freely</td><td>Agent shows diff, waits</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Test runs</td><td>Agent runs tests anytime</td><td>Agent asks before running</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Git commits</td><td>Agent commits with spec attribution</td><td>Agent shows commit message, waits</td></tr>
        <tr><td>External API calls</td><td>Agent calls APIs freely</td><td>Agent shows request, waits</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Vault</h2>
    <p>
      The vault section is the only place where API keys are authorized for agent use.
      If a key isn't listed as <code>authorized</code>, agents cannot access it — even if
      it exists in your system keychain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Keys are stored in your platform keychain via <code>haystack secret set KEY_NAME</code>.
      The vault section grants or denies agent access to those stored values.
    </p>

    <h2>GPG signing</h2>
    <p>
      Signing your HUMANFILE establishes T0 operator identity — the highest trust tier.
      Without a signature, the OS operates at T2 (named, unverified).
    </p>
    <pre><code>gpg --armor --detach-sign .haystack/HUMANFILE</code></pre>
    <p>The signature file (<code>HUMANFILE.asc</code>) is read at boot alongside HUMANFILE.</p>

